05260nam a22009855i 9780520923720DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20002001cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209237207 a10.1525/97805209237202doi  a(DE-B1597)521009  a(OCoLC)49851890  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aDG59.A2 7aHIS0020002bisacsh04a937/.062211 aAndo, Clifford, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aImperial Ideology and Provincial Loyalty in the Roman Empire /cClifford Ando. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2000] 4c©2001  a1 online resource (515 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aClassics and Contemporary Thought ;v600tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tList of Illustrations -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- t1. Introduction: Communis Patria -- tPART 1. ANCIENT AND MODERN CONTEXTS -- t2. Ideology in the Roman Empire -- t3. The Roman Achievement in Ancient Thought -- tPART 2. CONSENSUS AND COMMUNICATION -- t4. The Communicative Actions of the Roman Government -- t5. Consensus in Theory and Practice -- t6. The Creation of Consensus -- t7. Images of Emperor and Empire -- tPART 3. FROM IMPERIUM TO PATRIA -- t8. Orbis Terrarum and Orbis Romanus -- t9. The King Is a Body Politick . . . for that a Body Politique Never Dieth -- t10. Conclusion: Singulare et Unicum Imperium -- tWorks Cited -- tGeneral Index -- tIndex Locorum0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Roman empire remains unique. Although Rome claimed to rule the world, it did not. Rather, its uniqueness stems from the culture it created and the loyalty it inspired across an area that stretched from the Tyne to the Euphrates. Moreover, the empire created this culture with a bureaucracy smaller than that of a typical late-twentieth-century research university. In approaching this problem, Clifford Ando does not ask the ever-fashionable question, Why did the Roman empire fall? Rather, he asks, Why did the empire last so long? Imperial Ideology and Provincial Loyalty in the Roman Empire argues that the longevity of the empire rested not on Roman military power but on a gradually realized consensus that Roman rule was justified. This consensus was itself the product of a complex conversation between the central government and its far-flung peripheries. Ando investigates the mechanisms that sustained this conversation, explores its contribution to the legitimation of Roman power, and reveals as its product the provincial absorption of the forms and content of Roman political and legal discourse. Throughout, his sophisticated and subtle reading is informed by current thinking on social formation by theorists such as Max Weber, Jürgen Habermas, and Pierre Bourdieu.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAllegiancezRome. 0aPolitical stabilityzRome. 0aRoman provincesxAdministration. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh  aadministration.  aallegiance.  aancient rome.  aancient world.  aaugustus.  abody politic.  abourdieu.  abureaucracy.  acentral government.  achristian ideology.  aempire.  afall of the empire.  agovernment.  ahabermas.  ahistory.  aimperial identity.  amax weber.  anonfiction.  apolitical consensus.  apolitical stability.  apolitics.  apower struggle.  apower.  aprovinces.  aprovincial loyalty.  arevolt.  aroman emperors.  aroman empire.  aroman government.  aroman history.  aroman military.  aroman senate.  arome.  asocial formation.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052022067640uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520923